Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in weakly supervised segmentation for damage localization lies in bridging the gap between coarse bounding box supervision and fine-grained pixel-level predictions. Existing methods often rely on class activation maps (CAMs), which tend to activate only on the most discriminative regions, leading to incomplete or fragmented masks. Inspired by recent advances in vision transformers and attention mechanisms—particularly how self-attention can reveal spatial dependencies and saliency patterns—I propose a framework that co-evolves object detection and segmentation through iterative refinement of pseudo-masks guided by attention dynamics. Unlike prior works that use attention statically (e.g., for masking or synthesis), my idea leverages attention as a dynamic feedback signal within a transformer-based detection-segmentation pipeline. This allows the model to progressively expand and refine pseudo-segmentation masks by identifying uncertain or under-activated regions within the bounding box. Furthermore, while Paper 2 explores multimodal correction, I focus on unimodal RGB data but introduce temporal consistency via historical prediction ensembling and uncertainty-aware attention modulation—concepts not explored together in this context. By integrating attention-conditioned augmentation strategies (inspired by Paper 1) and diffusion-inspired mask regularization (motivated by Paper 3’s attention control), the proposed method enables more complete and spatially coherent damage localization without requiring any pixel-level labels. The key novelty lies in the bidirectional interaction between detection and segmentation heads, where refined pseudo-masks improve detection quality (via better feature alignment), and improved detection enhances segmentation (via tighter region proposals), forming a virtuous cycle.

