  "Idea": "We propose a transformative framework titled 'Causal Attention Intervention with Differentiable Boundary Optimization for Transformer-Based Pixel-Level Damage Localization under Bounding Box Supervision'. This work addresses a critical challenge in industrial AI: achieving accurate pixel-level damage segmentation without costly pixel-wise annotations. While existing weakly supervised methods rely on class activation maps (CAMs) or iterative refinement, they often fail to distinguish true damage from texture-similar backgrounds due to spurious correlations in feature activation. Our solution introduces a causality-driven paradigm within a dual-branch vision transformer architecture that jointly performs object detection and instance segmentation. The core innovation is the Causal Attention Intervention (CAI) module, which applies counterfactual reasoning to self-attention maps to identify and suppress confounding regions. Specifically, CAI computes a counterfactual activation score by masking out candidate regions in the attention map and measuring the drop in classification confidence; regions causing minimal change are deemed non-causal and down-weighted. This intervention is differentiable and integrated into training via a Causal Regularization Loss, forcing the model to focus only on structurally necessary features. To further enhance localization fidelity, we introduce a Differentiable Boundary Optimization (DBO) module that treats mask boundaries as noisy estimates and applies a diffusion-inspired gradient flow to smooth and close fragmented edges. DBO operates directly on the predicted mask probability map using a learned PDE-based kernel, encouraging topological coherence without requiring ground-truth contours. These two modules interact synergistically: CAI produces cleaner initial masks, which DBO then refines geometrically, while the refined outputs guide the detection head through an Attention-Aligned Feature Modulation (AAFM) mechanism that enhances region proposals with segmentation-informed attention weights. We train the entire system end-to-end using only bounding box labels, generating pseudo-masks via CAI-guided CAMs and refining them through DBO before backpropagating segmentation loss. The framework is evaluated on challenging benchmarks such as MVTec-AD, DAGM, and custom bridge inspection datasets, demonstrating superior performance in both detection (measured by AP) and segmentation (mIoU, Boundary F-score). By grounding weak supervision in causal principles rather than heuristic refinement, our method achieves higher generalization, robustness, and interpretability—making it ideal for safety-critical applications like infrastructure monitoring and manufacturing QA.",
